{{For|people named Bowtell|Bowtell (surname)}}
[[File:Abacus - architecture (PSF).png|thumb|right|Bowtell - upwardly expanding curved surface found beneath the [[Abacus (architecture)|abacus - rectangle found on top of column, labelled number 1]].]]

'''Bowtell''' is derived from the [[medieval]] term ''bottle'';<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=b1ovAAAAMAAJ&dq=Bowtell%20(medieval%20architecture)&pg=PA94#v=onepage&q=Bowtell&f=true  ''Treatise on architecture:...''], ed. Arthur Ashpitel, p. 94, (Edinburgh 1867). A round molding can also be referred to as a [[torus]].</ref> in [[architecture]] it refers to a round or [[cornice]]d [[molding (decorative)|molding]] below the [[Abacus (architecture)|abacus]] in a [[Tuscan order|Tuscan]] or Roman [[Classical order#Doric order|Doric]] [[Capital (architecture)|capital]]; the word is a variant of boltel, which is probably the diminutive of bolt, the shaft of an [[arrow]] or [[javelin throw|javelin]]. A roving bowtell is one which passes up the side of a bench end and round a [[finial]], the term roving being applied to that which follows the line of a curve.<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Bowtell|volume=4|page=349}}</ref>

