{{Infobox power station | name = Crivina Power Station | name_official = Termocentrala de la Crivina | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Romania | location_map_size = | location_map_caption= | coordinates = {{coord|45|02|1.59|N|21|48|57.69|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = Romania | location = [[Crivina, Caraş-Severin County|Crivina]] | status = D | construction_began = 1976 | commissioned = 1983 | decommissioned = 1988 | cost = | owner = [[Termoelectrica]] | operator = | th_fuel_primary = [[Oil shale]] | th_fuel_tertiary = | ps_units_operational= 3 X 330 | ps_units_manu_model = | th_cogeneration = | th_combined_cycle = | ps_electrical_capacity= 990 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac= | website = | extra = }} The '''Crivina Power Station''' ({{lang-ro|Termocentrala de la Crivina}}) was a large [[thermal power plant]] located in [[Crivina, Caraş-Severin County|Crivina]], near [[Anina]] in [[Caraş-Severin County]]. It had three generating units of 330&nbsp;[[Watt#Megawatt|MW]] each, altogether having a total [[electricity]] generating capacity of 990&nbsp;MW.<ref name=pace> {{cite journal | publisher = The Pace Company Consultants & Engineers | url = http://adr.coalliance.org/cog/fez/eserv/cog:2179/PACE_SFQR_V._19_N.1_1982.pdf | title = Direct Combustion of Oil Shale | journal = Pace Synthetic Fuels report | volume = 19 | issue = 1 |pages = 2–2 | format = PDF |date=March 1982 | accessdate = 2012-11-03}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/3283429/Energomontaj-IEA-Bucuresti|title=Principalele referinte|date=2009|work=Energomontaj|language=Romanian|accessdate=2010-09-17}}</ref> It was intended to be the first [[oil shale]] power station built in [[Romania]].<ref name="Anina - termocentrala muzeu">{{cite web|url=http://www.adevarul.ro/actualitate/Anina-termocentrala-muzeu_0_16799535.html|title=Anina - termocentrala muzeu|date=2002|work=Adevarul|language=Romanian|accessdate=2010-09-17}}</ref> The total cost of the [[oil shale]] power plant was around US$1 billion.<ref name="unit"/> The Crivina Power Station was supplied with 4 million tonnes of [[oil shale]] per year from the nearby [[Anina Mine]].<ref name="Anina - termocentrala muzeu"/>
==History== This power plant works only for 76 hours in reality. At the beginning of the 1970s [[Nicolae Ceauşescu]], then President of Romania, decided to build a large [[thermal power plant|thermal power station]] in [[Caraş-Severin County]] to exploit the large oil shale deposits located in the area.<ref name="anina">{{cite web|url=http://www.apropo.ro/news/util/orasul-frigului-2224837|title=Oraşul frigului|date=2001|work=apropo.ro|language=Romanian|accessdate=2010-09-17}}</ref> At first the power station was intended to be built in Ticvaniu Mic [[Communes of Romania|commune]], now part of the [[Ticvaniu Mare]] commune, near [[Oraviţa]] but the chosen site had a very small water supply that was not sufficient for the power station.<ref name="anina"/> In 1976 a new location was found at Crivina, located in the mountains near [[Anina]]. In 1983 the construction of the power station was complete and the first 330 MW electric power generation unit was put online. The turbine could not reach its highest potential capacity due to the low quality of the [[oil shale]] deposits.<ref name="anina"/> The communist regime also built a town that was used to house the power station's workers. It was intended to have 10,000 inhabitants, and a part of Anina had to move to this new location to make way for oil shale [[surface mining|surface mines]].<ref name="anina"/>
The first of the three power generation units was completed in 1983, and in 1984 generated its first electricity from burning oil shale.<ref name="unit">{{cite news |url= http://www.caon.ro/stiri/caras/articol/mult-zgomot-pentru-nimic/cn/news-20090330-04474486 |title=Mult zgomot pentru nimic |trans-title=Much ado about nothing |date=2009-03-30 |work=Caras Online |first= Nina | last = Curiţa |language=Romanian |accessdate=2010-09-17}} </ref> The unit functioned only around 2000 hours per year between 1984 and 1988 until it was shut down, its main generator having broken down and was sent to Bucharest for repairs, only for it to be sent to Rovinari in 1990. Eventually between 2003 and 2009, most of the power station was demolished and slowly sold for scrap.<ref name="unit"/> The station also had a {{convert|220|m|ft}} tall [[flue gas stack]] that was at the time Romania's second tallest.<ref name="unit"/>
